\details{
Internal Delta profile and surface helpers

Developer-facing documentation for the helpers that build grid-based and
optimizer-based \code{Delta} intervals and attach them to fitted objects.
\subsection{\code{delta_profile_value_scale(object)},}{

\code{delta_profile_initial_step(object)}, and
\code{delta_profile_interval_width(object)}

These helpers derive problem-specific scales for the \code{Delta} profile search.
They return, respectively, a characteristic \code{Delta} scale, the initial
outward step used when bracketing profile bounds, and the starting half-width
for the log-odds search interval. Their role is to keep the profiling
algorithm adaptive to the observed data rather than hard-coding a universal
search range.
}

\subsection{\code{delta_profile_target_tolerance(target, scale = 1)} and}{

\code{delta_profile_cache_key(x)}

\code{delta_profile_target_tolerance()} returns a numerical tolerance appropriate
for comparing candidate and target \code{Delta} values, while
\code{delta_profile_cache_key()} converts numeric inputs into a stable string key
for memoization environments. Their role is to control repeated candidate
evaluations without introducing avoidable floating-point mismatches.
}

\subsection{\code{delta_profile_lrt_candidate_factory(object, tol = 1e-8)}}{

Builds the parametric candidate closure used by the direct \code{Delta} profile
optimizer. The returned function maps a target \code{Delta} and a candidate
\code{logORdelta} into a full candidate object with implied \code{muDelta}, joint
statistic, arm-specific parameters, and the reconstructed \code{Delta}. Its role
is to reduce the direct profile problem to optimization over a single
log-odds coordinate.
}

\subsection{`delta_profile_splrt_mu_solver(reference, p0, p1, targetDelta,}{

tol = 1e-8)`

Solves the semi-parametric subproblem of finding the observed-outcome mean
difference \code{muDelta} that yields a requested \code{targetDelta} once \code{p0} and \code{p1}
are fixed. The helper returns a candidate list carrying feasibility, the
empirical-likelihood statistic, the arm-specific means, and the matched
\code{muDelta}. It uses root-finding when possible and falls back to minimizing the
squared \code{Delta} mismatch over the feasible range. Its role is to support the
direct profile interval for the semi-parametric method.
}

\subsection{\code{delta_profile_splrt_candidate_factory(object, tol = 1e-8)} and}{

\code{delta_profile_candidate_factory(object, tol = 1e-8)}

\code{delta_profile_splrt_candidate_factory()} builds the semi-parametric version
of the target-\code{Delta} candidate closure. \code{delta_profile_candidate_factory()}
dispatches between the parametric and semi-parametric builders based on
\code{object$method}. Both return closures that accept a target \code{Delta} and a
candidate \code{logORdelta}. Their role is to give the later optimizer a uniform
interface across methods.
}

\subsection{\code{delta_profile_objective_value(candidate)} and}{

\code{delta_profile_logor_near_boundary(logORdelta, lower, upper, frac = 0.05, tol = 1e-6)}

Small predicates used by the direct profile optimizer. The first converts a
candidate object into a scalar objective, treating missing or infeasible
candidates as very poor. The second flags whether the best current log-odds
location lies too close to the search boundary. Their role is to keep the
optimizer bookkeeping readable.
}

\subsection{`delta_profile_optimize_logor(candidate_fun, center, width,}{

expansion = 1.5, max_iter = 6, tol = 1e-6)`

One-dimensional search over \code{logORdelta} for a fixed target \code{Delta}. The
helper repeatedly expands a search interval around \code{center}, evaluates the
candidate closure and a direct \code{optimize()} call, and returns the best
candidate object it found. Its role is the core numerical engine for the
direct \code{Delta} profile interval.
}

\subsection{\code{delta_profile_factory(object, tol = 1e-8)}}{

Creates the memoized profile function \verb{targetDelta -> best candidate} for a
fitted object. The returned closure caches results by target \code{Delta}, returns
the fitted point with statistic zero when the target matches \code{object$Delta},
and otherwise delegates to \code{delta_profile_optimize_logor()}. Its role is to
expose a reusable profile function for interval inversion.
}

\subsection{`delta_profile_find_bound(profile_fun, estimate, crit,}{

direction = c("lower", "upper"), initial_step, tol = 1e-6,
max_expand = 24)`

Inverts a one-dimensional profile function to locate one endpoint of the
direct \code{Delta} profile interval. It returns a scalar bound or \code{NA_real_} if
the search cannot leave the acceptance region. Its role is to translate the
profiled statistic into interval endpoints after the candidate optimizer is in
place.
}

\subsection{`delta_profile_interval.optimize(object, conf.level = object$conf.level,}{

tol = 1e-6)`

Computes the direct optimizer-based \code{Delta} profile interval. It returns a
length-two numeric interval or \code{c(NA, NA)} when the fit is unsuccessful,
adjusted, lacks an atom, or the profiling search cannot find both endpoints.
Its role is to provide the slower exact-profile alternative to the default
grid-based approximation.
}

\subsection{\code{delta_boundary_touched(mask)}, `delta_surface_for_inference(object,}{

conf.level = object$conf.level, resolution = 31, offset = NULL,
expansion = 1.5, max_iter = 6)\verb{, and }delta_interval_from_surface(surface_data, threshold)`

These helpers support the default grid-based \code{Delta} intervals. \code{delta_boundary_touched()}
checks whether the accepted surface region hits the edge of the current grid.
\code{delta_surface_for_inference()} repeatedly evaluates the joint surface with
\code{include_delta = TRUE}, expanding the offsets until the accepted region is
interior or the iteration limit is reached. \code{delta_interval_from_surface()}
then takes the range of accepted \code{Delta} values under a supplied threshold.
Their role is to turn the same evaluated joint surface into either projected
or profile-style \code{Delta} intervals.
}

\subsection{\code{validateDeltaIntervalAlgorithm(algorithm)}}{

Validates the algorithm selector used by the public \code{confint()} method and the
internal wrappers. It returns either \code{"grid"} or \code{"optimize"} and errors on
any other value. Its role is to keep the algorithm switch centralized.
}

\subsection{\code{delta_projected_interval.grid(...)}, \code{delta_projected_interval(...)},}{

\code{delta_profile_interval.grid(...)}, and \code{delta_profile_interval(...)}

These wrappers expose the grid-based and optimizer-based projected/profile
\code{Delta} intervals behind uniform APIs. The \verb{*.grid} helpers always operate on
the expanded joint surface, while the higher-level wrappers dispatch on the
validated \code{algorithm} argument. Each returns a length-two numeric interval.
Their role is to keep the public confidence-interval code small while still
allowing slower exact alternatives for validation or sensitivity analysis.
}

\subsection{\code{augmentDeltaInference(object)}}{

Final augmentation step applied to successful fits. For unadjusted fits with a
known atom it computes the stored \code{Delta} point estimate, the Welch
\code{DeltaMarginalCI}, leaves \code{DeltaProjectedCI} as unavailable by default, and
stores the grid-based \code{DeltaProfileCI} as both \code{DeltaProfileCI} and the
backward-compatible alias \code{DeltaCI}. For failed, adjusted, or atom-less fits
it fills all \code{Delta} fields with \code{NA} intervals. Its role is to attach the
derived combined-outcome summaries only when they are methodologically
meaningful.
}
